               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Yohanan (1)’s student<ref corresp="#d2e16781"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>–</note>
               </state>
               <bibl>bBer21b<ref corresp="#d2e16794"/>(Kosowsky,Babylonico, 1685)</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>Fictitious?<ref corresp="#d2e16804"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>3rdC<ref corresp="#d2e16815"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e16781" n="102"> In the text ר' יהודה ור' שמעון
                            תלמידיו של ר' יוחנן
                    .</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e16794" n="103"> Although mentioned only
                            her in BT, he is designated רבי, see Introduction 5.1.3.2.2, and
                            transmits tradition in the name of the Palestinian Rabbi Yohanan (1),
                            see Introduction 5.1.3.2.3.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e16804" n="104"> The text
                            tells of Abdimi (1) (S-H/M - vol. 4, p. 318) coming to Babylonia and
                            transmitting a tradition in his name and in the name of Simon (32).
                            Usually ר' יהודה ור' שמעון are the famous Judah (30) B/M vol.1, p. 113
                            and Simon (51) B/M vol. 1, p. 220, but they cannot be students of
                            Yohanan (1). Thus I assume these are otherwise unknown students, from
                            Palestine of course, although it cannot be ruled out that they are a
                            literary invention of an early sage.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e16815" n="105"> Was the student of Rabbi
                            Yohanan (1), see Introduction 7.4.1.</note>
            </person>
